Two adult PEFAs were team hunting over the Slough. After each attempted to bird strike and missed, they focused on a dowitcher, forced the dowither to fly east of the slough, and within a few seconds one of them returned with the bird in its talons. The two circled together triumphantly over Ocean Meadows Golf Course for a while, then continued circling toward the north for several minutes. Clearly these Peregrines were tolerating each other and working together. In my scope I watched the bird with the dowitcher continue flying due north until it passed out of view. These Peregrines were paired, this is the middle of their breeding period, and the took off together heading north with their prey (they did not eat it at the slough). This combination of observations suggests to me that we may have a breeding pair near enough to Goleta to include Devereux within their home range.

Hunting at 9:42, then perched on the West side Eucs. Made many passes, focused mainly on Bonaparte's gulls but harassed lots of different birds. At 10:02 AM after long hatassment of a Marbled Godwit, the PeFa finally plucked the maimed godwit out of the water, carried it to the delta and finished it off. This was a labored flight due to the size of the godwit. Still eating the bird at 10:07 when I moved positions. Later I did not see the PEFA on the slough delta. Quite a hunting show.
